{{for|the album by Merzbow|Venereology (album)}}

'''Venereology''' is a branch of [[medicine]] that is concerned with the study and treatment of [[sexually transmitted disease]]s. The name derives from Roman goddess [[Venus (mythology)|Venus]], associated with love, beauty and fertility. A physician specializing in venereology is called a ''venereologist''<ref>{{cite web |title=Venerologist |url=https://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/venereologist |website=The Free Dictionary |accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref>. In many areas of the world, the specialty is usually combined with [[dermatology]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Journal of the European Academy of Dermatology and Venerology |url=https://www.wiley.com/en-us/Journal+of+the+European+Academy+of+Dermatology+and+Venereology-p-9780JRNL61760 |publisher=Wiley |accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref>.

The venereal diseases include bacterial, viral, fungal, and parasitic infections<ref>{{cite web|title=List of all STDs and their Symptoms|url=https://www.std-gov.org/stds/std_list.htm}}</ref>.  Some of the important diseases are [[AIDS|HIV infection]], [[syphilis]], [[gonorrhea]], [[candidiasis]], [[herpes simplex]], [[human papillomavirus]] infection, and [[scabies|genital scabies]]. Other sexually transmitted infections studied in the field include [[chancroid]], [[lymphogranuloma venereum]], [[granuloma inguinale]], [[hepatitis B]], and [[cytomegalovirus]] infection<ref>{{cite web |title=What you need to know about STDs |url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/246491.php |website=Medical News Today |accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref>.

In India, formal training of venerologists started in 1910, prompting microscopy and serology to come into general use throughout the Empire.  Before this, many cases of early syphilis were either diagnosed as chancroid or missed altogether. To come to a diagnosis, doubtful atypical cases were at times left untreated to see whether or not they developed secondary syphilis<ref>{{cite web |title=Venerology in India |url=http://www.e-ijd.org/article.asp?issn=0019-5154;year=2011;volume=56;issue=4;spage=363;epage=367;aulast=Thappa |website=Indian Journal of Dermatology |accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref>. Today, an MD in venereology is a 2 to 3-year long postgraduate course in medicine.  The minimum eligibility is the successful completion of any of MBBS, DMS, BHMS, and BDS, etc degrees.  Major subjects of study that form part of the program are immunology of dermatological diseases, cellular and molecular inflammation, skin genetics, skin structure and development of skin, and basic reactions of skin, repair, and carcinogenesis<ref>{{cite web |title=Doctorate of Medicine in Venereology |url=https://collegedunia.com/courses/doctorate-of-medicine-md-venereology |website=Collegedunia |accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref>.

