The '''Yentl Syndrome''' is the different course of action that [[Myocardial infarction|heart attacks]] usually follow for women than for men. This is a problem because much of medical research has focused primarily on symptoms of male heart attacks, and many women have died due to [[Medical error|misdiagnosis]] because their [[symptoms]] present differently. The name is taken from the 1983 film [[Yentl (film)|''Yentl'']] starring [[Barbra Streisand]] in which her character plays the role of a male in order to receive the education she desires. The phrase was coined in a 1991 academic paper by Dr. [[Bernadine Healy]] titled "The Yentl syndrome."

